I_{1} \dot{\omega}_{y} + I_{1} \Omega_{z} \omega_{x} - I_{3} \Omega_{x} \omega_{z} = M_{y} \\
I_{3} \dot{\omega}_{z} + I_{1} (\Omega_{x} \omega_{y} - \Omega_{y} \omega_{x}) = M_{z}
\end{array}\right.
\]

Note that the $\boldsymbol{\omega}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$ in the equations are not the same as the $\boldsymbol{\omega}$ and $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$ in the problem. Here, $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$ is the angular velocity of the $NKZ$ coordinate system, which moves with the precession of the rigid body, equal to the $\omega$ in the problem. Here, $\omega$ is the problem's $\omega + \Omega$, so do not confuse them. We do not change to the notation used in the problem until we derive formulas useful for this problem.

In general, the $NKZ$ coordinate system also moves with the precession and nutation of the rigid body, but not with its rotation. We can always align the $x$-axis with the $N$-axis.

\begin{align*}
\Omega_{x} &= \dot{\theta}, \quad \Omega_{y} = \dot{\varphi} \sin \theta, \quad \Omega_{z} = \dot{\varphi} \cos \theta \tag{2} \\
\omega &= \dot{\boldsymbol{\varphi}} + \dot{\boldsymbol{\theta}} + \dot{\boldsymbol{\psi}} = \boldsymbol{\Omega} + \dot{\boldsymbol{\psi}} \\
